One employee sustained moderate head injuries and was treated at the scene before being taken to hospital.
Haden Searles, the Durban-North uMhlanga Community Police Forum chairperson, said the robbers were “obviously” organised.
“They dropped off the car, then jumped into another car, taking the registration plates with them,” said Searles. He said the Urban Improvement Precinct (UIP) manager was near the shop and witnessed the thieves come out - one wearing a wig and women’s clothing.

“At least one of the suspects was armed with a rifle believed to be an AK47; it could have turned into a bloodbath should they (UIP) have engaged them there and then. It would have been a devastating experience with multiple restaurants and members of the public right there,” said Searles.AdChoicesADVERTISINGinRead invented by Teads
He said there was not much more that could have been done by the responding officers, and that people needed to be more alert.
“Be aware and alert, don’t be complacent - not that the people in the store were not alert, but we all need to be constantly alert.
“If people see something out of the ordinary and suspicious, they must report it ­immediately,” said Searles.

Jacques van der Merwe, from a nearby restaurant, said since the robbery it had been business as usual, with no complaints of people being fearful and no noticeable ­decrease in customers.
Deokaran said the police were working on leads, but no arrests had been made.
The Mercury